# No orphan words in visual design

An **orphan** (widow in body copy) is a **single word** stranded alone on the **last line** of a paragraph, heading, button label, or CTA—bad rhythm and looks unfinished.

## When editing this site

- **Reword** so the last line has at least two words, or roughly balances with the line above.
- **Tie the last two words** with a non-breaking space so they stay together: `last&nbsp;words` or the Unicode narrow no-break space between words that must stay paired.
- **Headings and short lines**: prefer `text-wrap: balance` in CSS where it fits (supported in modern browsers) so multi-line titles don’t leave one word alone.
- **Don’t** rely only on `<br>` for whole paragraphs unless it’s intentional poetry-style layout.

## Check after changes

Skim **hero**, **CTAs**, **section titles**, **project descriptions**, **footer**, and **buttons** at mobile and desktop widths; fix any line that ends with a lone short word.

## Examples

```html
<!-- ❌ Last line might render as one word: "requirements." -->
<p>…event requirements.</p>

<!-- ✅ Keep "event requirements" together -->
<p>…event&nbsp;requirements.</p>
```

```css
/* ✅ Help multi-line headings avoid a single word on the last line */
.section-title {
  text-wrap: balance;
}
```

If balance or copy edits can’t fix it without harming readability, **shorten or split the sentence** instead of leaving a visual orphan.
